  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing internal AML control programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on AML procedures\n\n4. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining financial transaction documentation\n\n5. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Regulatory sanctions\n\n6. International Standards\n- Adhering to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Complying with international anti-money laundering protocols\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and detect potential money laundering activities.",
